column1: When will a date for general elections in Denmark be announced?
column6: ['Foreign Policy', 'Elections and Referenda']
Election anounced yesterday.

I don't know why this question still existing, but I think I have the most reliable in hand. Reference https://www.reuters.com/article/us-denmark-election/denmarks-prime-minister-calls-election-to-be-held-on-june-5-idUSKCN1SD180
Election announced today
5/7/19 news reports, elections announced for June 5 date:
This just happened.
The news media have been buzzing with rumors that election date is very imminent. I'm adjusting my prediction because of this.
Update: Today, Tuesday 7th May 2019, PM Rasmussen called the general elections for June 5th 2019.
Update: Today the Prime Minister has called a general election in Denmark for June 5th. So, i was right, but they are not going to occur during the European elections (on 26th May), as I assumed.

Update: During the writing of my last update Prime Minister Lars Løkke Rasmussen announced that the general election will be held on the 5th of June. Note to self, always check the news before posting a new update.

Forecast update #6: General elections were announced today. They are going to take place on June, 5 2019, also Constitutional Day in Denmark. (https://ekstrabladet.dk/nyheder/politik/danskpolitik/article7624437.ece) Even though my forecast was right in terms of the date, I have to critically reassess that my basic assumption was wrong. I assumed they were hold on the same day as EU parliamentary elections. Due to the usual 20-22 days of campaigning in Denmark, I concluded the time period between April 1, and May, 15.

Update: As the date for the general election was not announced before 1 April, that options is no longer possible. I chose to move the percentage to the second options, between 1 April and 15 May. However, as the 15 May is fast approaching, I chose to change my original forecast to 60% in favour of option 2, and 40% in favour of option 3. This is based on the fact that most parties are currently busy campaigning for the EU elections, and the same argument that I made in my original forecast; as the conservative block keeps declining in public support, they could wish to watch the polls before calling for a new election. With that being said, polls cannot be trusted, which is why the second option still gets a higher percentage.
Update: announcement made today and is set for June 5th

According to danish news platforms and historical data concerning previous general elections in Denmark when they coincided to be in the same year as the European elections, it is highly likely for Danish elections to be in the same dates as European elections. For this a good sources and historical analysis is provided by @Eveli here: https://www.gjopen.com/comments/comments/831494 .
FWIW: An excerpt from the 5/5/19 news article linked below:
Forecast update #5:

Update: As I've mentioned before, the 30th of April seemed reasonable for announcing elections. However, the date for general elections has not been yet revealed. I still believe the idea of holding both elections (General elections in Denmark and European Parliament Elections) on the same date is a convenient option for the current government.
I believe that the date of the general elections will be announced at some point in the next 4 days.
Adjusting, mainly for passage of time..

Almost all big political reform are being closed in the parliament right now. I think if the pension reform will be negotiated in place today or tomorrow (the agreement between the government parties) , than their is big chance for that Lars Løkke will press the election button - on Wednesday or Thursday.

Forecast update #4: I still very much believe that both EU parliamentary and General Elections will be hold together. However, given the fact that in the past campaigning took always 20-22 days and the EU elections will behold on 26 May there are only 7 till 9 days left to announce the date, which is why I increased the likelihood of option number 3 slightly by adding the two percent of option #1, without decreasing the likelihood of option #2.

Update: Løkke is currently negotiating an agreement on a new retirement plan for those who have worked physically demanding jobs ('seniorpension til nedslidte'). He will most likely want this finalized before the election, as this has been one of the Social Democrats major talking points. He could likely close the deal very soon and make it in time to announce the election on May 26th. However, if his polling numbers do not improve, he'll might choose to push the election date into June. (As my previous update indicating, this would also put him in a favorable position to the EU commissioner negotiations). I believe that we should be watching the polls around May 1st to gauge if he he holding the election in late May or in June.

Update: it is inching closer to May 15 and there an announcement is yet to be made. Rasmussen's Venstre party is fairing poorly in the polls at just 19% as of April 17 (https://pollofpolls.eu/DK) -- giving him a possible incentive to push the announcement (and election) back to after the EU election. The forecast has been adjusted to account for an increased chance of the election being called after May 15.
UPDATE

Update: Venstre and Løkke have are still falling behind in the polls. Venstre's proposed reform of the health care system (sundhedsreformen) failed to make an impact and did not gather the attention expected. Consequently, Løkke could choose to push the election further back and have the general election after the EP elections. If the Danish election is held in June, Løkke would still be acting prime minister during the negotiations on the commissioner positions. This would leave him in a favorable position as he seeks a political office outside of Denmark.

Update: no interesting changes in the last week. I have found an article about the concerne of Danish government in a foreign influence during the election campaign. In particular, the government is concerned because Russia might launch a campaign to and influence opinions ahead of the election. However, no news about the announcement of the election day.

According to the Danish Constitution, the elections should be held no later than June 17, 2019. The last election took place on June 18, 2015 and four years need to pass since last elections in order to hold another one this year. Besides, the announcement should be made at least 3 weeks before the election date. The announcement in Denmark is always made on Tuesdays as well.

General elections will have to be held before the 17th of June 2019. Announcing the date only after the 15th of May is rather short-term, and as an election needs some preparation and planning this would probably not be sufficient time to do so. On the other hand it would be better for the ruling party to make the election time as short as possible as to do limit the possibilities of the opponents to create effective campaigns.

Updating my forecast: The "before 1 April" bracket is no longer possible. My opinion of the relative probability of the other two options hasn't changed, so I'm just raising their probabilities by equal amounts.
Update: As the 1st of April is passed I suppose I higher probability of the election day announcement between 1 April and 15 May

First, it is necessary to set some parameters. The last election was June 18, 2015 (https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/jun/18/denmark-election-result-too-close-to-call-as-exit-polls-suggest-no-clear-winner) which means that elections must be held before the same date of this year. Additionally, the election date would likely be set three weeks in advance (see above question). This means that the last theoretical day that it could be announced would be May 28. That gives 13 days for the "After May 15th" category for this to happen. As it is currently past April 1st, there is a 0% chance for that category. Lastly, we have the middle category. Unless Denmark announces their elections in the next 45 minutes, there are 35 days where the announcement could happen. There are five weekends in this time frame, so there are 25 days when this could happen on or before May 15th, and 9 days (2 weekends) for after May 15th. That being said, I believe it is also unlikely that the Danish Government would announce elections on a public holiday, and there are 4 holidays occurring on a weekday between now and the time when a date would likely need to be set (April 18, April 19, April 22, and May 17, from https://publicholidays.dk/2019-dates/). So now, there are 22 days before May 15th, and 8 days after. Simple math gives us that there are 22/30 probable days the Danish Government would announce for April 1-May 15, and 8/30 days for after May 15.

The elections' date has still not been announced, which turns the first possibility to a 0%. As we are speaking about the date in which it will be announced the elections' day - and not the elections' day itslef - I'd say that it's more probable an incoming notification rather than a late one
5% because the Danes don't seem like they leave things to the last minute
Annotation: Option 1 “Before 1 April 2019” can be excluded as no announcement has been published until now = 0%
Update: we have passed April 1 without an announcement.
..Closer to overall forecast consensus
Updating for passage of time
Late forecast so the option one i out. Unless something extraordinary will happen in the weekend.

Updating my previous forecast: It is almost April 1st and the election date have not been announced. The government and the Danish People's Parti have recently agreed on health care reform, but the reception of the reform program have been mixed. Because of this I am decreasing the probability of an election announcement before April 1st from 40% to 15%. According to news journalists with inside knowledge a May 26th election is still the most likely option. An argument for this would be that Lars Løkke Rasmussen is more experienced in international and EU politics and he might want to use this to his advantage in the election campaign and in debates. Therefore having a national election close to the European might be very likely. He could still use this after the EU election so I'm increasing the probability of both the "1st April-15th May" option (from 50 to 60%) and the "After May 15th" (from 10 to 25%).
Forecast update #3: only two more days to go for option #1. so probability reduces further.
Passage of time
Passage of time update

Update: Taking into account that there are 5 days left before April and that Rasmussen's party is behind the Social Democrats (approx. 8.75 difference), there is no chance he will call for elections this week. Hence, the chances for the Prime Minister to call for elections between April 1st and May 15th are increasing, giving more weight to the probability of holding the Danish elections at the same time as the European elections.

The election must be held before the 17th June, and it takes 3 weeks notice to hold an election, so the latest it can be announced is the end of May. Presuming they won't leave it until the very last possible minute, it should be announced by the 15th May.

Adjusting: as it is almost April, the chance that the date will be announced until then, is even less likely. In addition, I increase the chances of the date to be announced between 1 April and 15 May 2019 due to the same reasons expressed in the analysis before (holding Danish elections together with EU elections).
Just arbin' dumb money vs. smart. First bucket nearing close out.

Forecast update #2: Time period till April 1 is running out without any news which, decreases the likelihood of an announcement before April 1, which is why the forecast at hand updates its earlier estimation as following: 3% less likelihood the announcement will take place before April 1, 3% higher likelihood of the announcement between April 1 and May 15.

As it inches closer to April 1, the probability of the announcement being made before then is rapidly decreasingly. It still appears to be in the strategic interest of Rasmussen to hold the Danish elections around the same time as the EU elections, meaning the announcement should be made between April 1 and May 15.

Update: Current polls show that the opposition 6.8% points ahead of Løkke and his blue coalition (Altinget.dk). Hence, it's even less likely that Løkke will call an election before April 1st. Yet, it still seems likely that Løkke will hold the Danish parliamentary election alongside EU elections on May 26th, and the election will be announced between April 1st and May 15th.
A date for the general election must be announced at least weeks before the 17th of june. In effect, this means that the latest possible date of announcement will be on the 27th of May.
Passage of time update
Still a tough call - but feel (from reading) led me to be heavy on Apr1-May15. Need to stay on top of this.
Elections need to be held before 17th of june 2019, an announced is at least three weeks earlier, making the latest possible date of announcement on the 27th of May.
..Closer to forecast consensus

Before 1 April 10% The average trendline of the Danish opinion polls towards the general election in 2019 shows that the current government is suffering a loss of support by the Danish population. Instead, the opposition “red bloc” is scoring points. https://pollofpolls.eu/DK In order to re-gain some votes the blue bloc would have better to don’t announce now the election, this would be a very bad timing for it. According to the current situation, Rasmussen, the current Prime Minister has better to wait.

1. The forecast at hand assumes a 10% likelihood for an announcement of the election day before 01/04. The last 4 general elections were all announced 20-22 days before the election day (Wikipedia - only English source available). Thus, if announced before 01/04 it would be very likely the elections would take place at the end of April. Not only would Eastern (public holidays: 18/04-18/22) fall into this period, where many Danish people might be on vacation but there would be also a second campaign necessary right in the aftermath due to EU parliament elections between 23/05 - 26/5. This would challenge both financial and human resources for Rasmussen’s Venstre, and the blue block (as well for all the other parties). From Rasmussen’s perspective, who is responsible for calling out the elections (and thus can use this as a strategic tool) this double load would only make sense if he could secure its majority that way. However, its social democratic opponent Frederiksen is leading the polls at the moment, both in terms of party comparison (Venstre: 17% | Socialdemocrats 25.8%) and block comparison (blue block: 44.4% | red block: 51% (without the party Alternativet, which is also considered a red party)) (http://cphpost.dk/news/election-prospects-look-grim-for-government-in-latest-poll.html). This record low will hardly motivate Rasmussen for an early election move. It is furthermore regarded as rather unlikely by the forecast at hand that this trend will change in this short amount of time - without a drastic external shock.

Firstly, let’s look at the legal temporal limit for the current government in charge to hold the Danish elections. This must be on or before 17 June 2019. If we look at the previous patterns, the last 3 general elections were announced at least 3 weeks before the day of the vote. Furthermore, in the last decade, general elections have all been given a campaign period of around 20 days. Therefore, after this initial brief analysis we can already assess as highly unlikely that the government will announce general elections after the end of May. However, this does not exclude completely none of the given possibilities.

The last three general elections (2015, 2011, 2007) were announced 3 weeks before the elections. Following that, it could be considered that the likelihood that in 2019 the same trend will be followed and the time frame will be similar is high. However, this year an additional factor is the EU election. Retrospectively, three times the Danish General Election occurred the same year as the EU election (1979, 1984, 1999) and none of these times, they were held together. Nevertheless, it can be explained by the distance between the elections (national general election were held in September-January while EU elections - in June). What is different, this year, considering the time, general election and EU election happen to be very close to each other. Therefore it can be expected that the decision will be made to arrange general election together with the EU (which is in May23-May26). Hence, it should be announced before the 15 of May. To be more precise, my guess is the beginning of May.
Adjusting again, mainly per forecaster input/consensus.

There is quite a bit of agreement among political commentators in Denmark that a national election happening after the European Parliament election is unlikely. The reasons include voter fatigue because of extensive campaigning and the upcoming summer holidays. To me it seems as solid arguments, and I therefore forecast only a 10% chance of the election being announced after May 15th.

The sitting government holds a tactical advantage in being able to select the election date, provided of course it falls before June 17. A strategical decision will thus be made to better their chances at winning the most votes and forming a new government.

Based on Voxmeter's weekly opinion polls (https://voxmeter.dk/meningsmalinger/#), which show that the "blue block", aka the right and conservative block, which is currently in power, is slowly declining, I believe that it would be natural for the government to wait to announce the date of the election longer then 1 April. Seeing as the announcement must occur three weeks before the election day, and that one can assume that the conservative block would prefer a short campaign period (http://theconversation.com/time-to-learn-the-many-lessons-from-a-long-campaign-62048), it is my opinion that after the 15 May is not completely unlikely. As it would be favourable for the conservative block to have as short as possible campaign period, if their popularity continues to decline. However, announcing after the 15 May also seems unlikely, as this might be a too short time window for the campaign, which is why I land at 65% chance for between 1 April and 15 May 2019, as this will allow the conservative block to regain the popularity in the opinion polls, while at the same time allow for a somewhat short campaign period.

15% Before 1 April 2019: Setting a date for general elections is a prerogative of running governments, and an important card to play. Venstre party is not having favourable polls at the moment, and might be willing to buy some more time in order to get to the election day in better condition.

The alternate fortune the actual government is having in a relatively short period - see https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-08-20/danish-premier-catches-up-on-main-opponent-in-credibility-poll , https://www.thelocal.dk/20181022/danish-government-party-hits-worst-poll-figures-in-15-months and http://cphpost.dk/news/election-prospects-look-grim-for-government-in-latest-poll.html - could not nonetheless explain an election as early as before the 1st of April - as the deadline is the 17th of June. This is the reason why I give only a 5% probability to this outcome. On the other side, a loss in popular consense could call for an early election, even though a strong probability can be attributed to a normal 4 years mandate. P.S. Some of the indicated sources in the forecast's question can be misleading - check the year in which articles are writte, e.g. the first article suggested was written 8 years ago, it has a limited explanatory power...

5% Before 1 April 2019 : Very unlikely. Considering that the Prime Minister has no particular interest in exceeding the usual 3 weeks campaign, calling for elections before 1 April 2019 would mean that the Prime Minister is calling for early elections. However, time has proven that the Prime Minister will most likely call for elections at a time were his/her party is in strong position, that is, the Prime Minister usually keeps a close eye to the polls. In that sense, acknowledging that the current opinion polls on the Danish government party hit particularly low figures, it is unlikely that Løkke Rasmussen will announce the elections date before the 1 April 2019. In other words, it is expected that Løkke Rasmussen will try not to precipitate the elections in the next weeks.

15% - Before April 1, 2019 Maybe Lars Løkke Rasmussen will announce the elections before April 1st if he sees in polls a majority of opinion favorable for his "blue" coalition. Indeed, the announcement of the elections is often perceived as a tactical advantage for the sitting government, often announcing the elections when the polls are favorable. However, as trends poll show in institute such as Voxmeter, Megafon, Gallup and Norstat, the blue coalition does not have on average a majority of favorable voting intentions since May 2016, and the gap is growing more and more each month since this date, where since the end of October 2017 it is seen at the head of polls 6 times out of 69 studies, updated weekly. This therefore tends to show the announcement of an election before April 1 as unlikely, as it seems that the blue coalition will not be seen as a favorite by then.
Adjusting, in part per input of other forecasters.

There are a few key points to keep in mind in relation to this forecast. Firstly, in October 2018 Prime minister Lars Løkke Rasmussen announced that the Danish European elections will take place on Sunday May 26th 2019 (DR.dk). Secondly, the last six general elections have had a campaign period of between 20-22 days (Altinget.dk). There is no reason to believe that Løkke desires a long campaigning period. In a bid to ensure high voter participation in both the European election and the Danish general election, it is likely that Løkke will hold both elections on the May 26th. A similar joining of votes occurred in 2009, when the European elections were held on the same day as the vote on the Succession Referendum. However, it is also worth noticing that a Danish general election has never been held on a Sunday and in doing so, Løkke would break with tradition (ft. dk).

Per others: . 2015: election announced May 27 and held June 18 . 2019: election must be held by June 17 . 2019: EU elections May 23-26 Will they call it last minute? Consensus calling it last minute and running quick process supports status quo (if polls/trends are looking good). I didn’t read of any benefit to early election call (longer campaign). Will they combine with EU elections (in which case announcement required in April)? Given efficiency of Danish system, think they’ll keep them separate. Unaware of any potential impact at EU level driving earlier/combined parliamentary elections. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Opinion_polling_for_the_2019_Danish_general_election

The European Parliament election of 2014 in Denmark was an election held in Denmark on 25 May 2014 to decide who would represent Denmark in the European Parliament (EP) from 2014 to 2019. The Danish People's Party with 26.6% of the votes became the largest party for the first time in a nationwide Danish election.

After 15 May only leaves 4 weeks, which makes it less likely than the 6 week time span from 1 Apr to 15 May. Not sure if or how Brexit may impact, but perhaps they'll wait until after Brexit date has passed?
Adjusting forecast somewhat per current GJP consensus..
It is unlikely that the government would move up their elections since they do not have to be held until June 17th at the latest.

Seems based on what @sreichau wrote, that lining up with the european elections is the most likely outcome. As well, given the ruling coalition's unpopularity, I think the party wants to have elections later rather than sooner.

A few base assumptions: 1) Lars Lokke Rasmussen, the Prime Minister and Venske party leader will call elections at the most opportune moment for their party to win the most votes 2) Looking at the last 6 elections, the time between the election being called and the election date was 20-22 days (could not find exact date for when the 2001 election was called, but it says 'less than 3 weeks' before the election day here [1]. So assuming 21 days between election call date and election date. This gives 4th May 2019 for the most likely day for elections if the intent was to have them coincide with the European elections (23rd-26th May). Following this logic, the latest date for elections to be called would be 27th May.

As per Danish Constitution elections must be held no later than June 16th. The PM has the right to call elections earlier than that date, based on polls. Apparently, back in October it was not doing well in polls [1], but it seems it is recovering from the 17.3% to 18.4%. But another member of the Blue Bloc (supporting the government), the Danish People's Party DPP, drops from 18.2% to 16.2% [2].

Quick considerations for an initial forecast: - The last general election was announced in late May 2015, and took place on June 18, 2015. The 2019 election must be held by June 17, 2019, according to this source. (Minimum three weeks advance notice is required:) https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2019_Danish_general_election
